Module kivakit.core
Package com.telenav.kivakit.core.time

Class Duration

java.lang.Object
com.telenav.kivakit.core.time.Duration
All Implemented Interfaces:
DoubleQuantizable, Quantizable, QuantumComparable<LengthOfTime<?>>, Stringable, StringSource, LengthOfTime<Duration>, TimeMeasurement, Comparable<LengthOfTime<?>>
public class Duration extends Object implements LengthOfTime<Duration>
A Duration is an immutable length of time stored as a number of nanoseconds using BigDecimal.

Important Note on Precision

Some convenience methods take or produce double values, which are only precise up to 2^53 nanoseconds, or approximately 0.285 years (at this time). If it is desirable to avoid imprecision for values larger than this, avoid using these methods, and the nanoseconds() method will provide the fully-accurate underlying BigDecimal value.

Creation

These static factory methods allow easy construction of value objects:

  • nanoseconds(double)
  • nanoseconds(double, Restriction)
  • microseconds(double)
  • microseconds(double, Restriction)
  • milliseconds(double)
  • milliseconds(double, Restriction)
  • seconds(double)
  • seconds(double, Restriction)
  • minutes(double)
  • minutes(double, Restriction)
  • hours(double)
  • hours(double, Restriction)
  • days(double)
  • days(double, Restriction)
  • weeks(double)
  • weeks(double, Restriction)
  • years(double)
  • years(double, Restriction)

Conversion

The precise number of nanoseconds represented by a Duration object can be retrieved by calling the nanoseconds() method. The value of a duration object in a given unit like days or hours can be retrieved by calling one of the following unit methods, each of which returns a double-precision floating point number:

  • TimeMeasurement.asMicroseconds()
  • TimeMeasurement.asMilliseconds()
  • TimeMeasurement.asSeconds()
  • TimeMeasurement.asMinutes()
  • TimeMeasurement.asHours()
  • TimeMeasurement.asDays()
  • TimeMeasurement.asWeeks()
  • TimeMeasurement.asYears()
